Reflection

EDA has been performed by looking at variables/features behaviour in univariate, bivariate and multivariate plots/summaries. These plots/summaries are tools to discover important relations among variables. The main interest of this exploration is to get to know what variables/features impact red wines quality.

Interesting relations came up, like the one between alcohol and quality grades. According to this relation If I have to choose among red wine bottles I should look for the one with highest alcohol level (% by volume) because this one will be the one with the highest quality.

Investigations across internet showed me that fixed acidity and citric acid are closely related, in fact; citric acid is a fixed acid (the other ones being tartaric, malic and succinic) so its natural that as citric acid increases, fixed acidity also increases. According to this relation If I have to choose among red wine bottles considering wines with less than 0.50 citric acid (g/l or its equivalent in other units) I should look for the one with the lowest fixed acidity, and above 0.50 citric acid (g/l or its equivalent in other units) the one with the highest fixed acidity. These ones will be the ones with the highest quality.

Investigations across internet showed me that density and alcohol are closely related. During alcohol fermentation, yeast converts sugars into carbon dioxide and alcohol. The decline in the sugar content and the presence of ethanol (alcohol which is appreciably less dense than water) drop the density of the wort (decreasing overall density). According to this relation if I have to choose among red wine bottles considering wines with less than 12.5 alcohol level (% by volume) I should look for the one with the highest density, and above 12.5 alcohol level (% by volume) the one with lowest density. These ones will be the ones with the highest quality.

Evaluating wines is a complex skill and its subjective (depends on sommelier). I can see that highest (0.7) or lowest (-0.7) correlation coefficients values were obtained among variables/features that by nature (chemical properties) are highly related. If we were talking about something different than wines we would expect these coefficients to behave similar (this is the case for fixed acidity vs citric acid). The variables/features that impact quality are not really identified because low values above 0 and high values below 0 are obtained in correlation matrix so these values are not helping me to identify important relations. Im not expert about wines but I guess dataset needs more variables/features to discover the ones that really impact wines quality.
